Bacon, however, is not always consistent in his abuse of Aristotle. Sometimes he speaks of him in terms of eulogy, as. for instance, in Aph. 98 and in the following passage of the Redargutio Philosophiarum: ‘ltaque bos duos viros, Platonem et Aristotelem, si quis inter maxima mortalium ingenia non numerat aut minus perspicit aut minus aequus est?

The specific charge against Aristotle that he subordinated his natural philosophy to bis logie is undoubtedly founded in part on his partiality for the technical forms and terminology of the syllogism. This circumstance often obscures his argument (as we may see even in the oth and yth Boolrs of the Ethics), and also often has a tendency to divert his attention l'rom the arbitrary or questionable character of the principles on which his reasoning proceeds. But under the phrase ‘¹ logicae suae,’ Bacon probably includes not only ‘ logic' properly so called, but also the metaphysical dis- tinctions which are of such frequent occurrence in Aristotle's works. Instead of explaining physical phenomena in their true relations or by reference to their true causes, Aristotle frequently, if not generally, deems it sufficient to bring them under bis metaphysical distinctions of δύναμις and ἐνέργεια, matter, form, and privation, the four causes, the ten categorias, the different kinds of motion, and the like. Of. this tendency we have a notable instance in the De Coelo, where we should naturally expect to lind a careful account of observed facts with reference to the earth and the heavenly bodies; instead of this account, however, we have interminable discussions on substance, qualities, the various kinds of motion, and other topics ofa like rnetaphysical character. The title of tbis treatise, bow· ever, was not given by Aristotle himself.
